{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620088"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16613"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0,0.02,0,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66046"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9304"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5249"},{"type":"tags","id":"10135"},{"type":"tags","id":"10145"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22083"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66046"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAromatase inhibitors are commonly used in the treatment of hormone-sensitive breast cancer in postmenopausal women.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Block oestrogen receptor binding","Suppress gonadotropin release","Stimulate progesterone production","Increase oestrogen degradation","Prevent conversion of androgens to oestrogens"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAromatase inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing the conversion of androgens to oestrogens\u003C/strong\u003E. They specifically inhibit the aromatase enzyme, which is responsible for the final step in oestrogen biosynthesis. This reduces circulating oestrogen levels in postmenopausal women, where most oestrogen is produced in peripheral tissues rather than the ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking oestrogen receptor binding\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of selective oestrogen receptor modulators like tamoxifen. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing oestrogen degradation\u003C/strong\u003E is not how these drugs work - they prevent oestrogen synthesis rather than increasing its breakdown. \u003Cstrong\u003ESuppressing gonadotropin release\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of gonadotropin-releasing hormone analogues. \u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating progesterone production\u003C/strong\u003E is not related to aromatase inhibitor action, as aromatase inhibitors do not affect progesterone levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAromatase inhibitors are particularly effective in postmenopausal breast cancer because they can block the peripheral production of oestrogen that occurs in adipose tissue and other sites.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aromatase inhibitors block the conversion of androgens to oestrogens by inhibiting the aromatase enzyme.","Aromatase inhibitors are used in postmenopausal women with oestrogen receptor-positive breast cancer.","Examples of aromatase inhibitors include anastrozole, letrozole and exemestane."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T09:22:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T09:22:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9304"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66046"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine